Royal Kitchen is one of those staples of old Hawai'i if you grew up in town. It's just some place you went, like Char Hung Sut or Shimazu.  And cleanliness is a definite issue. That being said, it's for baked manapua (nope, neither Char Hung Sut nor Libby's does baked manapua; do not even ask or you will be covered in stink eye fo' DAYS).  When you go, there will be two doors, one facing the canal and one facing a building. Go into the one facing the canal. Pull a ticket immediately. Wait in line.  Accepts credit cards.  No public bathroom. You'll need to use the one in the Chinese Cultural Plaza, but this isn't really a place to hang out anyway. You can eat your food on a curb outside or at one of the little stone benches along the canal, tho best bet is to grab-and-go.  Shop is too small for a stroller to fit comfortably if there is a line, so be prepared to wiggle your way around if needed.  There is free validated parking for 30 minutes if you park in the back. Remember to bring your ticket with you, and let them stamp it.  The Char siu in their char siu baked manapua is always in large shreds; no mystery meats here. Light spices, very soft buns. Smaller than Chun-wah Kam in Kalihi, but a staple all the same.  The ladies here have always been super nice to me and my family. They never remember us, but they're pretty nice to everybody. Sometimes they'll even throw in an extra manapua if you buy a dozen. We love that. Always reliable taste, if at times the buns are a little under proofed. We wish it was in a nicer spot, but with free parking and sweet old ladies running the front, we come back again and again. Thank you Royal Kitchen!

OK, upon arrival in honolulu, my wife and i set to find the best manapua and best shave ice. A few years back my wife remembered she really like a baked manapua from one of these stores, but couldn't remember which one. Royal Kitchen was on the list for baked versions, so we hit this station first. They make a really good manapua, but later we tried Chun Wah Kam Noodle Factory and that was the one my wife really liked. Overall, I'd give Royal Kitchen a B+ for their baked manapua. As for their pork hash (or we call it shiu-mai), the kids preferred this over the ones at Libby's.
